entries.title: Here’s the latest on the riot in the Brazilian capital.
Your Tuesday Briefing: Brazil Arrests Rioters
entries.description: Also, heavy fighting rages around Bakhmut and scientists say the ozone layer is healing.

entries.title: What We Know About Investigations Into the Brazil Protests
entries.description: Investigators face several major questions as they piece together how rioters briefly seized the seats of Brazil’s government.

entries.title: Prince Harry Memoir Signals Bigger Royal Rift
entries.description: The self-exiled royal has given the world a warts-and-all look at his family — with an emphasis on the warts.

entries.title: Adolfo Kaminsky Dies at 97; His Forgeries Saved Thousands of Jews
entries.description: His talent for creating realistic documents helped children, their parents and others escape deportation to concentration camps, and in many cases to flee Nazi-occupied territory.

entries.title: Czech Court Clears Andrej Babis of Fraud in E.U. Funds Case
entries.description: Andrej Babis, a billionaire agriculturalist, had been accused of illegally obtaining farm subsidies for one of his properties.

entries.title: Has Prince Harry’s ‘Spare’ Changed Public Opinion of Him?
entries.description: Even in the United States, which has a high tolerance for redemptive stories about overcoming trauma and family dysfunction, the tide seems to be turning.

entries.title: French Food Giant Danone Sued Over Plastic Use Under Landmark Law
entries.description: Environmental groups are relying on a law in France requiring large companies to address their environmental footprint.

entries.title: Restoration of the Ozone Layer Is Back on Track, Scientists Say
entries.description: Rogue emissions from China of ozone-depleting chemicals had threatened to delay recovery by a decade. But the emissions were stopped, according to a U.N.-backed report.

entries.title: Shifting Strategy, Ukraine Goes Toe to Toe With Russia in Bakhmut
entries.description: Earlier in the war, Ukraine’s leadership was more equivocal about pitched battles with high casualties. There’s no second-guessing this time. Some analysts say it makes sense strategically.

entries.title: Putin’s Efforts to Divide the West Over Ukraine Fall Flat
entries.description: A cease-fire proposal seemingly aimed at splintering Western unity has instead been met with Western escalation, underscoring Moscow’s diplomatic struggles.

entries.title: Ukraine Rejects Russia’s Claim of 600 Killed in Kramatorsk Attack
entries.description: Russia’s Defense Ministry said it had carried out a strike that “killed 600 people,” but no evidence has emerged to support the claim.

entries.title: Live Updates: Mass Arrests in Brazil After Anti-Democracy Riots
entries.description: Scores were taken into custody after supporters of Jair Bolsonaro, Brazil’s far-right former president, stormed official buildings in the capital to protest what they falsely believe was a stolen election.

entries.title: Tempo of Conflict Slows 10 Months Into the War
entries.description: Weather is factor as less territory changes hands, but both Russia and Ukraine have sent signals about possible new offensives.

entries.title: A Dysfunctional Congress
entries.description: Congressional gridlock brought on by far-right Republicans now seems more likely to lead to government shutdowns.

entries.title: Skatepark Near Colosseum Gives Rome a Modern Tourist Spot
entries.description: The ancient city’s leaders hope the new recreation area will lure more visitors from abroad. It has already impressed the talent at home.

entries.title: In Power With Netanyahu, Ultra-Orthodox Parties Chart Israel’s Future
entries.description: Bolstered by growth in numbers and political influence, ultra-Orthodox parties are pushing for greater autonomy, with potentially far-reaching implications for the country.

entries.title: Your Monday Briefing
entries.description: Here’s what you need to know.

entries.title: What We Learned From Prince Harry’s ITV and ‘60 Minutes’ Interviews
entries.description: Two days before the publication of his memoir, “Spare,” Harry appeared at ease and at times emotional in high-profile interviews in the United States and Britain.

entries.title: Here’s what to know about the protest fueled by false claims of electoral fraud.
Brazil’s Protests Resemble the US Capitol Attack on Jan. 6
entries.description: Jair Bolsonaro, the right-wing former president of Brazil, had for months sought to undermine the results of an election that he lost, in much the same manner that Donald J. Trump did after his defeat in the 2020 presidential election.

entries.title: Who Is Jair Bolsonaro?
entries.description: The former president of Brazil upended political norms as a far-right populist.

entries.title: Videos Show How Rioters Stormed Brazil’s Capital
entries.description: Watch key moments of rioters attacking Brazil’s Congress, Presidential offices and the Supreme Court.

entries.title: Bolsonaro Supporters Lay Siege to Brazil’s Capital
entries.description: Thousands of supporters of former President Jair Bolsonaro invaded Brazil’s Congress, presidential offices and Supreme Court, denouncing what they falsely claim was a rigged election.
